      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is an established economic principle that generous welfare benefits create a significant disincentive to work, which is clearly reflected in the data. When the reward for staying in a low-wage job is less than the benefit received while not working, the rational choice for many is to reduce labor supply. This is not a debatable theory; it is a measurable outcome of poorly structured social spending that undermines the work ethic.",
      "source": "target",
